description:
In lichen_lora_l2_init() at lines 569-573:
```c
lora_data.lora_dev = LORA_DEV;
lora_data.rx_callback = NULL;
lora_data.rx_callback_user_data = NULL;

if (!device_is_ready(lora_data.lora_dev)) {
    LOG_ERR("lora_l2: device not ready");
    ret = -ENODEV;
    goto out;
}
```

LORA_DEV is defined as DEVICE_DT_GET(DT_ALIAS(lora0)). The BUILD_ASSERT at line 181-183 ensures the device tree node exists. device_is_ready() checks if the device is actually ready to use.

If device_is_ready() returns false, we return -ENODEV. But we've already set lora_data.lora_dev to LORA_DEV. On failure path, lora_data.lora_dev retains the (potentially unready) device pointer.

Since we stay in LORA_UNINIT state (lora_transition is never called on this error path), subsequent calls to init() will re-enter and overwrite these values. The is_running() check at lines 564-567 returns early if state != UNINIT.

Wait, line 564-567:
```c
if (lora_get_state() != LORA_UNINIT) {
    k_mutex_unlock(&lora_mutex);
    return 0;
}
```

If init failed (stayed in UNINIT), next init() call will retry. The lora_data fields will be re-written. No leaked state.

NO BUG - idempotent retry is handled correctly.
